- Unsound financial information leads to inaccurate assessments of financial health and resource allocation.
- Management decisions based on faulty data can result in inefficiencies and errors.
- Poor financial information undermines the ability to plan and execute programs effectively.
- Inaccurate financial data can cause misalignment of priorities and objectives.
- Reliance on unsound information increases the risk of financial mismanagement and oversight failures.
- Sound financial information is essential for accountability and transparency in management.
- Agencies need accurate data to evaluate program performance and make informed decisions.
- Unsound information can lead to a lack of trust and credibility in management practices.